WEBVTT

00:00:00.880 --> 00:00:05.200
Hi folks, my name is Kristin Bott and I'm coming to you as one of the co-leads for the Pride

00:00:05.200 --> 00:00:10.080
Employee Resource Group at PawsitPBC. Today I'm going to be talking about building community at

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:16.480
work. Now thinking about ways that folks tend to approach this, I think it's very classic to do

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:21.920
big things. So maybe you bring in a speaker to approach a somewhat heady topic like how to be

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:29.760
your authentic self at work. Or there's always the classic drag bingo. Now I think this is a really

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:34.240
fun thing to do. People love this as an event. This is something we do at Pawsit every year.

00:00:34.959 --> 00:00:39.599
And people tell us things like, oh my kids really look forward to it. This is one of the highlights

00:00:39.599 --> 00:00:43.759
of our summer. And come on, who doesn't love a queer dance break in the middle of the workday?

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:49.759
So this is a great event. This is something we want to keep. And yet we wanted to see what else

00:00:49.759 --> 00:00:55.040
might meet the needs of our community. What else could we do? Maybe one way to think about this

00:00:55.040 --> 00:01:00.480
is if you have a big event, you have a speaker or an entertainer, you have people listening.

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:06.320
They're all paying attention to that one speaker. But if you take the speaker away,

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:10.800
you provide an opportunity for people to connect with one another.

00:01:11.919 --> 00:01:19.120
So idea number one, how about a coffee break? This is 45 minutes. We do this monthly. Bring

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:24.160
whatever beverage you have to have. Join when you can. Leave when you have to. So this is a nice

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:29.599
place to chat in a relatively small group. You can do things like meet people's pets or see their

00:01:29.599 --> 00:01:34.800
apartments. You can hear about their latest art project or talk about the weather. And sometimes

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:41.360
this is also the right environment for more deep and involved conversations like how are you really

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:48.400
doing? This has landed really well with people. And yet what else can we do? Who could we reach

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:56.239
by doing something slightly different? Enter the pride game break. This is half an hour every month.

00:01:56.239 --> 00:02:01.839
We get folks together and do something fun, play some kind of game together. So we've had Jeopardy,

00:02:01.839 --> 00:02:07.519
trivia games, drawing games like Gartic Phone. I think this works really well because it gives

00:02:07.519 --> 00:02:14.320
people a third thing, something to do together, something to connect through without the same

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:21.279
dynamics as a direct full-on conversation. Okay, that's great. What else? The newest addition to

00:02:21.279 --> 00:02:26.479
our lineup is something we're calling Queer Lightning Talks. So yes, you have the dynamic

00:02:26.479 --> 00:02:31.679
I described earlier of people all paying attention to the same person, but the presentations are short

00:02:31.679 --> 00:02:37.440
and the people speaking are our own. Topics are completely open-ended, work, non-work, whatever

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:43.600
folks choose to speak about. Some recent talk topics include a deep dive on animal communication

00:02:43.679 --> 00:02:48.800
from someone with a PhD in neuroscience, a story complete with visuals about the challenging

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:54.240
journey of knitting your first pair of socks, a run-through of a previous iteration of this talk,

00:02:55.039 --> 00:02:59.279
and a five-minute walkthrough of how to turn yourself from a human into a creature from

00:02:59.279 --> 00:03:05.039
another planet. And while these topics are all light and fun, sometimes things get a little more

00:03:05.039 --> 00:03:11.039
interesting. So one of our members is known for fantastic clubbing outfits, and so we asked him

00:03:11.039 --> 00:03:15.839
to put together some slides about that. And this turned into a really interesting discussion

00:03:15.839 --> 00:03:20.080
of costumes versus outfits and how what you wear intersects with your identity.

00:03:21.279 --> 00:03:26.960
So that's all well and fine and fun, but the question we're probably asking ourselves as

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:33.520
data-based people is, is any of this working? So I asked our membership what they thought,

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:39.919
and I received far more feedback than I could fit on this slide, but here are some key quotes for

00:03:39.919 --> 00:03:44.000
those messages. And I'll pause for a minute here so you have a chance to read.

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:57.839
And of course you can come back to the slides later. So to briefly close out, to echo one of

00:03:57.839 --> 00:04:03.279
our community members on that last slide, I think community is built through the many small actions.

00:04:03.279 --> 00:04:07.440
You don't need big events, you don't need a big budget. If you're trying to get folks together,

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:12.880
consider providing multiple options. And if you have a new idea, give it time before you decide

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:16.880
whether it's a success or a failure. And of course, always stay plugged into your community

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:21.600
and get feedback. Thank you all so much for listening, and a shout out to all of our Pride

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:26.959
ERG co-leads, current and past, as well as our executive sponsors. I'd love to talk about any

00:04:26.959 --> 00:04:31.679
of this, so please do get in touch. Thank you so much.

